05774nam a22008655i 9780812293111DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20162016pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979970133  a97808122931117 a10.9783/97808122931112doi  a(DE-B1597)474704  a(OCoLC)953602331  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aDS918b.H94 2016eb 7aHIS0230002bisacsh04a951.904/22231 aHwang, Su-kyoung, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aKorea's Grievous War /cSu-kyoung Hwang. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2016] 4cÂ©2016  a1 online resource (264 p.) :b21 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPennsylvania Studies in Human Rights00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tNote on Transcriptions and Testimonies -- tList of Abbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. Terror in Cheju Island -- tChapter 2. Emergency Laws and the Crisis of Human Rights -- tChapter 3. Ideological Persecution and the Massacre of 1950 -- tChapter 4. Observing Political Violence in Korea -- tChapter 5. Politics of Fear in the Bombing of Korea -- tChapter 6. The Bereaved Families -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1948, two years before Cold War tensions resulted in the invasion of South Korea by North Korea that started the Korean War, the first major political confrontation between leftists and rightists occurred on the South Korean island of Cheju, where communist activists disrupted United Nations-sanctioned elections and military personnel were deployed. What began as a counterinsurgency operation targeting 350 local rebels resulted in the deaths of roughly 30,000 uninvolved civilians, 10 percent of the island's population.Su-kyoung Hwang's Korea's Grievous War recounts the civilian experience of anticommunist violence, beginning with the Cheju Uprising in 1948 and continuing through the Korean War until 1953. Wartime declarations of emergency by both the U.S. and Korean governments were issued to contain communism, but a major consequence of their actions was to contribute to the loss of more than two million civilian lives. Hwang inventories the persecutions of left-leaning intellectuals under the South Korean regime of Syngman Rhee and the executions of political prisoners and innocent civilians to "prevent" their collaboration with North Korea. She highlights the role of the United States in observing, documenting, and yet failing to intervene in the massacres and of the U.S. Air Force's three-year firebombing campaign in North and South Korea.Hwang draws on archival research and personally conducted interviews to recount vividly the acts of anticommunist violence at the human level and illuminate the sufferings of civilian victims. Korea's Grievous War presents the historical background, political motivations, legal bases, and social consequences of anticommunist violence, tracing the enduring legacy of this destruction in the testimonies of survivors and bereaved families that only now can give voice to the lived experience of this grievous war and its aftermath.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aKorean War, 1950-1953. 7aHISTORY / Asia / Korea.2bisacsh  aAfrican Studies.  aAmerican History.  aAmerican Studies.  aAsian Studies.  aHistory.  aHuman Rights.  aLaw.  aMiddle Eastern Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Packagez978311064982608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2016z9783110485103oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2016z9783110485189oZDB-23-DEG